JUNIOR LEVEL (10 Questions)

Q1: What is the QEMU boot sequence?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

1. main() → qemu_init() (parse args)
2. machine_init() (create machine)
3. device_init() (create devices)
4. load_firmware() (load BIOS)
5. qemu_create_cpus() (create vCPUs)
6. creation_done() → vm_start() (resume VMs)

</details>

Q2: What is QMP?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

QEMU Management Protocol (JSON-RPC over socket). For programmatic control of QEMU. Used by OpenStack, libvirt, etc. Replaces human monitor (HMP).

</details>

Q3: What is the x86 reset vector?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

At address 0xFFFF0 (just below 1MB). First instruction after CPU reset. Jumps to BIOS entry point (0xF000:0xE05B). QEMU loads BIOS here.

</details>

Q4: What is QAPI?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

QEMU API schema definition language. Defines QMP commands, structures, and types. Generates C code for command dispatch and serialization. Single source of truth.

</details>

Q5: What is the difference between QMP and HMP?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

QMP: JSON-RPC, machine-readable, for automation. HMP: human-readable, interactive, for debugging. HMP commands are deprecated in favor of QMP.

</details>

Q6: What is qcow2?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

QEMU Copy-On-Write version 2. Disk image format with features: snapshots, compression, encryption, sparse files. Default format for QEMU.

</details>

Q7: What is the qcow2 header?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

First 64 bytes of qcow2 file. Contains: magic, version, cluster_bits, size, L1 table offset, refcount table offset, snapshot table offset, etc.

</details>

Q8: What is qemu-img?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Command-line tool for disk images. Commands: create, convert, info, resize, snapshot, check. Works with qcow2, raw, qed, etc.

</details>

Q9: What is a cluster in qcow2?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Allocation unit in qcow2. Default 64KB. Smaller clusters = less waste, larger clusters = faster I/O. Must be power of 2.

</details>

Q10: What is a snapshot in qcow2?

<details>
<summary><b>Answer</b></summary>

Point-in-time copy of disk. Uses backing file chain. Changes after snapshot go to new file. Can revert to snapshot. Overlay file doesn't affect base.

</details>

